# Behavior protocol

This is the **canonical behavior reference** for Claude's memory operations.
The most critical procedure (daily standup) is also inlined into `MEMORY.md`
so it runs even if this node isn't read. Everything else lives here and is
read on demand.

## Path conventions

All bash examples in this document use these environment variables.
Define them at the top of any procedure:

```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"
STATE="$MEM/state.md"
COUNTER="$MEM/state_counter"
JOURNAL="$MEM/journal"
NODES="$MEM/nodes"
INDEX="$MEM/MEMORY.md"
```

When Claude executes any command from this protocol, it must use these
absolute paths — never bare `state.md` or `nodes/` (which would resolve
relative to whatever the current working directory is, usually the
project root, not the memory directory).

## At session start

The trigger and output format are duplicated in `MEMORY.md` for guaranteed
execution. This node has the same procedure plus extra detail.

## Daily standup (full procedure)

### Trigger detection

The trigger is based on the presence of a `## Session ` header in today's
journal file, **not** on mere file existence. This way, if a previous
session crashed after writing the standup block but before writing any
session block, the next session will refresh the standup instead of
silently skipping it.

```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"
STATE="$MEM/state.md"
JOURNAL="$MEM/journal"
TODAY=$(date +%Y-%m-%d)

if [ -f "$JOURNAL/$TODAY.md" ] && grep -q "^## Session " "$JOURNAL/$TODAY.md"; then
  echo "Not first session of day — skip standup, proceed normally"
else
  echo "First session of day (or previous session crashed before writing a session block) — running standup"
  cat "$STATE"
fi
```

### Stale marker computation

For each item in state.md, parse the date (`- [ID] YYYY-MM-DD: ...`),
compute `age = today - date`, and append `[stale: N days]` if `age >= 14`.

### Orphan node check

Orphans = files in `$NODES/` not referenced from `$INDEX` either by
markdown link (`nodes/foo.md`) or Obsidian wikilink (`[[foo]]`).

```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"

for f in "$MEM/nodes/"*.md; do
  basename=$(basename "$f")
  slug="${basename%.md}"
  if ! grep -qF -e "nodes/$basename" -e "[[$slug]]" "$MEM/MEMORY.md"; then
    echo "Orphan: $basename"
  fi
done
```

`grep -qF -e A -e B` searches for **fixed strings** (no regex escaping
needed). The check passes if either the markdown-link form or the
wikilink form is present. If any orphans exist, list them in the
standup under `### Untracked nodes`.

### Standup output format

```
## Daily standup — <YYYY-MM-DD>

### Ship blockers
- [ID] YYYY-MM-DD: description — see journal/YYYY-MM-DD [stale: N days if applicable]
(or _(empty)_ if no items)

### Blocked
(items or _(empty)_)

### Ready for review
(items or _(empty)_)

### WIP
(items or _(empty)_)

### Open threads
(items or _(empty)_)

### Untracked nodes
(orphan files, or omit this section entirely if none)

---
```

### Standup rules

- **Empty section** but others non-empty → write `_(empty)_` so the check is visible
- **All sections empty AND no orphans** → skip standup entirely, proceed normally
- **Standup writes itself to today's journal file** — creates it if missing,
  or replaces an existing stale standup block (see below)
- **Section order matches state.md priority:** Ship blockers → Blocked →
  Ready for review → WIP → Open threads → (Untracked nodes if any)
- **Each item:** copied verbatim from state.md plus optional `[stale: N days]`
- **Ship blockers ≥14 days old** are doubly bad — surface with extra emphasis
  if they appear (consider also flagging to the user explicitly)

### Writing the standup block to the day-file

```bash
TODAY=$(date +%Y-%m-%d)
DAYFILE="$JOURNAL/$TODAY.md"

# If the file already exists but has no session yet (previous attempt
# crashed between standup write and session block), strip the stale
# standup before writing a fresh one. Matches the block starting at
# "## Daily standup" up to and including the first "---" line.
if [ -f "$DAYFILE" ] && ! grep -q "^## Session " "$DAYFILE"; then
  awk '
    /^## Daily standup/{flag=1; next}
    flag && /^---$/{flag=0; next}
    !flag
  ' "$DAYFILE" > "$DAYFILE.tmp" && mv "$DAYFILE.tmp" "$DAYFILE"
fi

# Then append (or create) with the new standup block.
# Leading "# YYYY-MM-DD" heading only if creating a fresh file.
```

### On-demand standup

User can ask for it any time, mid-day:
- "show me the standup"
- "what's still blocked?"
- "what's WIP?"
- "what needs my review?"
- "what's stale?"

Run the same procedure but skip the first-session-of-day check.

## When Claude writes a new node

Claude auto-creates a node when:
- **Feedback:** user corrects Claude ("don't do X") or confirms a
  non-obvious choice ("yes, that's right")
- **User fact:** user mentions something stable about role, expertise,
  preferences, communication style
- **Project fact:** user reveals a non-obvious decision, constraint, or
  gotcha not in code or git history
- **Reference:** user points Claude to an external resource

Claude does NOT auto-create a node for:
- Anything already in `CLAUDE.md`
- Code patterns visible in the repo
- Ephemeral context for the current task only
- Things that contradict an existing node — instead Claude flags and asks

Before writing: grep `$MEM/nodes/` for keywords from the new fact. If a
similar node exists, update it instead. See [[conventions_node_format]]
for the duplicate-prevention rules.

## When Claude updates an existing node

- Same statement (same rule, same domain, same scope) → update existing,
  bump `updated` date
- If the rule itself changed → mark old version `Superseded_by:` and create new
- New aspect of related topic → create new node + mutual `Related:` links

## When Claude writes a journal entry

At session end, IF any of:
- One or more files were changed (created/modified/deleted)
- An architectural/scoping decision was made
- Something left intentionally incomplete (open thread, status tag)
- A node was created or significantly updated

Claude does NOT write a journal entry for pure Q&A or single trivial edits
(e.g., a 1-line fix with no surrounding decisions).

When writing: append a `## Session N` block to `$JOURNAL/$TODAY.md`
(creates the file if it's the first session of the day, including any
standup block already there).

Session number `N` = count of existing `## Session ` headers in the
day-file + 1 (the standup block does not count).

See [[conventions_journal_format]] for the section structure and the
`A`/`M`/`D` Files-touched format.

## Session close trigger (proactive flush)

When the user signals they're about to end the session — phrases like
"close this session", "I'll start a new one", "wrap up", "ending here",
"I might have to go", or any similar intent-to-disconnect — treat it as
an explicit instruction to flush memory **in the same turn**, before the
sign-off response.

Flush checklist:
1. Write a `## Session N` block to `$JOURNAL/$TODAY.md` if any substantive
   work happened (per "When Claude writes a journal entry" above).
2. Update `$STATE`: close done items by ID, file open threads / WIP
   with fresh IDs from `$COUNTER`.
3. Save any pending feedback / user / project nodes, update `$INDEX`.
4. Write back the incremented `$COUNTER` if IDs were assigned.

Rationale: once the user ends the conversation, any pending memory is
lost. Deferring ("I'll write it later") is unreliable. The close signal
itself is the trigger — do not require the user to separately say
"update memory". See [[feedback_session_close]].

## State.md update protocol

`state.md` must stay in sync with what's actually open. Claude updates it
**incrementally** as state changes — there is **no batch validation pass**.
Get it right at the time, or fix it manually later.

### Item format

Each line in any state.md section follows this exact format:

```
- [ID] YYYY-MM-DD: short description — see journal/YYYY-MM-DD
```

- **`[ID]`** — stable monotonic integer identifier (see "ID generation" below)
- **`YYYY-MM-DD`** at start — **when the item was first added** (not today's date)
- **description** — short, ≤80 chars, what the item is
- **`see journal/YYYY-MM-DD`** — anchor back to the session that opened it
  (the date matches the start date above)

Example:
```
- [42] 2026-04-05: legal review for MSL token format — see journal/2026-04-05
```

### ID generation

IDs are **monotonic integers**, never reused, never recycled. Next ID
lives in the `state_counter` file as a single integer. Read it, use it,
write back `id + 1`:

```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"
COUNTER="$MEM/state_counter"

# Read next ID (default to 1 if file is missing or empty)
next_id=$(cat "$COUNTER" 2>/dev/null | grep -oE '^[0-9]+$' || echo 1)

# Use $next_id in the state.md line you're adding...
# e.g. echo "- [$next_id] $TODAY: description — see journal/$TODAY" >> "$STATE"

# Then increment the counter
echo $((next_id + 1)) > "$COUNTER"
echo "Assigned ID: $next_id, next will be $((next_id + 1))"
```

**Why a separate counter file instead of `max(state.md)`:** if the user
(or Claude) removes the max-ID item from state.md, `max(state.md)` would
reassign that same ID to the next new item — re-using an ID that still
lives in journal history under a different meaning. The counter file
survives state.md edits and guarantees true monotonicity.

**Counter recovery:** if `state_counter` is missing or corrupted, rebuild
it from max observed across state.md and all journal files (see
"Recovery procedures → Lost ID counter" below).

IDs survive section moves: if an item moves from `## WIP` to
`## Ready for review`, it keeps the same ID.

### Add to state.md when

- A session adds tag `#wip` → add line to `## WIP` with new ID
- A session adds tag `#blocked` → add line to `## Blocked` with new ID
- A session adds tag `#ship_blocker` → add line to `## Ship blockers` with new ID
- A session adds tag `#ready_for_review` → add line to `## Ready for review` with new ID
- A session has items in `### Open threads` → add each to `## Open threads` with new IDs

When adding, also mention the new IDs in the session's `**State changes:**`
field for reference (see [[conventions_journal_format]]).

### Remove from state.md when

- The current session's `### Done` mentions the item's ID → remove that line
  from state.md by ID match (reliable, not text-based)
- User explicitly marks something resolved
- User manually edits state.md (just respect the edit)

### Closure pattern

When closing an item, the journal `### Done` line **must** include the ID:

```markdown
### Done
- Closed [42]: legal review approved by legal team
- Closed [44]: verified multi-company behavior, all green
```

Then state.md removal is mechanical:
```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"
sed -i '/\[42\]/d' "$MEM/state.md"
sed -i '/\[44\]/d' "$MEM/state.md"
```

Or done in-line as part of the journal write. The `**State changes:**`
session field should also reflect closures:

```markdown
**State changes:** added [45] open thread, closed [42], closed [44]
```

### Stale items — two thresholds

There are two distinct thresholds for "old" items, used for different
purposes:

- **14 days = informational warning.** The daily standup adds
  `[stale: N days]` to items aged ≥14 days. Doesn't require action — just
  visibility, so old items don't sit in the periphery forgotten.
- **30 days = cleanup candidate.** The user-initiated monthly health check
  lists items aged ≥30 days as candidates for removal or refresh. Ask the
  user to run it (or wait for them to ask "what's stale?").

Why two thresholds: 14 days catches "this is sitting longer than I expected"
early without crying wolf on every old item. 30 days is when you should
actually decide if it's still relevant.

Neither threshold causes automatic removal. The marker is informational
only.

When you see a stale item, decide:
- Still relevant → leave it, update its date if anything new happened
- No longer relevant → remove the line manually or ask Claude to close it
- Forgot about it → remember and act

