## When Claude reads memory

- **Always (auto):** `MEMORY.md` — loaded by Claude Code's auto-memory system,
  contains the standup procedure and the node index
- **Auto at first session of day:** `state.md` (for standup)
- **On demand (any time):** `state.md` for "show me the standup" or similar
- **On demand:** individual nodes — Claude greps by topic, reads matches,
  follows `[[wikilinks]]`
- **Read once per conversation if needed:** convention nodes
  (`conventions_*.md`) — heavier (~500-3000 tokens each), don't re-read
  multiple times in the same conversation
- **On request:** journal entries — only when continuity is needed
  ("what did we do last time?")

## Token budget

- `MEMORY.md` is the only thing always in context. Keep under ~2k tokens
  (~200 lines, whichever comes first). The session-start procedure inside
  it is part of this budget.
- `state.md` is loaded once per day at standup time, plus on demand. Keep
  it focused — periodic cleanup of stale items is the main cost control.
- Nodes are read individually, ~100-300 tokens each. 3-5 per session is normal.
- Convention nodes (`conventions_*.md`) are heavier (~500-3000 tokens) but
  read at most once per conversation.
- Journal entries are NEVER in context unless explicitly requested.

## Recovery procedures

### Missed journal entry

If Claude forgot to write a journal entry at session end:

> "Write a journal entry for what we just did this session."

Claude reconstructs from conversation context and appends to today's
journal file. Best-effort — earlier conversation context may be compressed.

### Missed state.md update

> "Update state.md based on what we just did."

Claude reviews the session, identifies status tags and open threads,
adds corresponding state.md entries with new IDs (and removes any closed
ones).

### Wrong journal entry

Journal files are plain markdown. Edit any entry manually with any
editor. Claude reads what's there next time it consults a journal file —
no caching.

### Wrong state.md content

Same — edit manually. State.md is the single source of truth and Claude
respects whatever is in it.

### Lost ID counter

If `state_counter` is missing, corrupted, or you start fresh, rebuild it
by scanning all live sources for the maximum ID ever seen, then adding 1:

```bash
MEM="__MEMORY_DIR__"
STATE="$MEM/state.md"
COUNTER="$MEM/state_counter"
JOURNAL="$MEM/journal"

max_state=$(grep -oE '\[[0-9]+\]' "$STATE" 2>/dev/null | tr -d '[]' | sort -n | tail -1)
max_journal=$(grep -rhoE '\[[0-9]+\]' "$JOURNAL" 2>/dev/null | tr -d '[]' | sort -n | tail -1)
max_id=$(printf '%s\n%s\n' "${max_state:-0}" "${max_journal:-0}" | sort -n | tail -1)
echo $((max_id + 1)) > "$COUNTER"
echo "Counter rebuilt: next ID = $((max_id + 1))"
```

Rebuilding from journals (not just state.md) is important — closed items
no longer live in state.md but their IDs are still referenced in past
journal entries, and we don't want to reassign them.

To **explicitly reset** to 1: make sure state.md has no items AND no
journal references to any ID, then `echo 1 > "$COUNTER"`. This should
only be used on a fresh install.
